{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17507485","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17507485"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:53:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:53:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2629"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583328","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583328"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:13:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:13:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2629"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2629","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2629"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.23,0.11,0.63,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2629"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110289"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2629","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2629"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2629"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92560"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"42"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"414"},{"type":"tags","id":"4945"},{"type":"tags","id":"4967"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5631"},{"type":"tags","id":"5725"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11631"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2960"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3031"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27070"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33377"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39969"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44983"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110289","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/110289"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 54-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic requesting a complete genome sequencing test. She has been reading about it online and discussing it with her friends. She explains how it can find rare genetic disorders by identifying defects in the genes. She does not have any particular concerns, symptoms, or health anxiety. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She is very keen to get the test done as part of her \u0022routine screening\u0022 and wonders why it is not offered more regularly to patients.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate action to take?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Order the genome sequencing test as requested","Explain to her why she does not need the test","Refer her to a genetic counsellor","Provide education about screening programs","Ask her about symptoms of rare genetic conditions"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario highlights the growing role of patient curiosity and autonomy in healthcare, particularly as access to medical information online becomes more widespread. The patient is clearly engaged and proactive in thinking about her health, which is commendable. She has taken an interest in genomic testing and is motivated by the idea of prevention and early detection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile her interest in genome sequencing reflects a desire to take control of her health, it\u0027s important to guide her through the difference between investigational testing and population-based screening. In evidence-based medicine, screening programs are developed carefully to ensure that they do more good than harm. For a test to be offered routinely to people without symptoms, it needs to meet certain criteria: it should be safe, simple, affordable, and able to detect a serious and relatively common condition for which effective treatment exists, ideally one where early intervention improves outcomes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough genome sequencing is a powerful diagnostic tool for people with certain clinical indications or family histories, it\u0027s not currently supported for general population screening. It can lead to incidental findings, uncertainty, and unnecessary anxiety, especially when detecting rare conditions for which there may be no effective intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this context, the most appropriate next step is to respectfully explore the patient\u0027s goals and \u003Cstrong\u003Eprovide education about screening programs\u003C/strong\u003E that are recommended for someone of her age and background. This allows for a collaborative discussion that honours her interest in prevention, while also supporting clinical decision-making based on established public health principles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAsk her about symptoms of rare genetic conditions\u003C/strong\u003E is unlikely to help in this case and would include a very large, broad symptom set. Without any clinical indication, this approach would be inefficient and potentially anxiety-provoking.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Cstrong\u003Eexplaining why she does not need the test\u003C/strong\u003E may seem like a good option, a more appropriate approach would be to improve the health education of the patient, provide further details about screening programs and their indications to allow the patient to develop their own educated conclusion. This helps to empower the patient to comply with current recommended screening programs if they have a better understanding of the requirements they must meet.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERefer her to a genetic counsellor\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if there were specific genetic concerns or family history warranting further investigation. In this case, without any clinical indication, this referral would be an unnecessary use of specialist resources.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOrder the genome sequencing test as requested\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as there is no clinical indication for this expensive and potentially problematic test. Complete genome sequencing can generate complex results that may identify variants of uncertain significance, leading to unnecessary anxiety and follow-up testing. Additionally, these tests are expensive (around $1000) and require substantial resources to complete and interpret properly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore, the most effective and appropriate action to take in this situation is patient education and explaining why these types of tests are not available as screening programs to the entire population. This approach respects the patient\u0027s autonomy while providing evidence-based guidance about appropriate preventive healthcare.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Complete genomic sequencing is a diagnostic tool for specific clinical indications, not a recommended screening test for the general population.","Screening programs must meet specific criteria including disease importance, suitable testing methods, and available interventions.","Patient education about evidence-based screening is preferable to unnecessary genetic testing without clinical indication."],"references":["Dobrow MJ, Hagens V, Chafe R, Sullivan T, Rabeneck L. Consolidated principles for screening based on a systematic review and consensus process. CMAJ. 2018 Apr 9;190(14):E422-E429. doi: 10.1503/cmaj.171154. PMID: 29632037; PMCID: PMC5893317. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29632037/","Gonzaga-Jauregui C, Lupski JR, Gibbs RA. Human genome sequencing in health and disease. Annu Rev Med. 2012;63:35-61. doi: 10.1146/annurev-med-051010-162644. PMID: 22248320; PMCID: PMC3656720. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22248320/","Royal Australian General Practitioners, 2016. Red Book: Guidelines for preventative activities in general practice 9th edition. Access at: https://www.racgp.org.au/download/Documents/Guidelines/Redbook9/17048-Red-Book-9th-Edition.pdf.","Lee CE, Singleton KS, Wallin M, Faundez V. Rare Genetic Diseases: Nature\u0027s Experiments on Human Development. iScience. 2020 May 22;23(5):101123. doi: 10.1016/j.isci.2020.101123. Epub 2020 May 1. PMID: 32422592; PMCID: PMC7229282. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32422592/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92560"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2629"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"92560","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/92560"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-29T15:01:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-29T15:01:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2629"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"110289"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"38","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/38"},"a